extends layout

block content
  .theory-hero
    .container
      .theory-hero-badge Topic 7 — Hash Functions
      h1.theory-hero-title Anatomy of a Block
      p.theory-hero-subtitle
        | How a Bitcoin block is structured, how blocks link into a chain,
        | and why cryptographic hashing makes the ledger tamper-proof.
      p.theory-hero-meta
        | Based on: S. Nakamoto, &ldquo;Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System&rdquo; (2008)

  .container.theory-body

    //- ── Section 1: The Trust Problem ────────────────────────────────────────
    .theory-section
      h2.theory-section-title
        span.theory-section-number 1
        | The Problem: Trust Without Authority
      .theory-callout
        .theory-callout-quote
          | &ldquo;What if two parties could transact directly,
          | without the need for a trusted third party?&rdquo;
        .theory-callout-author — Satoshi Nakamoto, Bitcoin Whitepaper (2008)
      p
        | The core challenge is the <strong>double-spend problem</strong>: how can we prevent
        | someone from spending the same digital coin twice — without a bank to check the ledger?
      p
        | Blockchain converts a <strong>problem of trust</strong> into a
        | <strong>mathematical problem</strong>. The solution rests on three cryptographic tools:
      .theory-tools-grid
        .theory-tool-card
          .theory-tool-icon ƒ
          h4 Hash Functions
          p Link blocks and summarise transactions using one-way, collision-resistant functions.
        .theory-tool-card
          .theory-tool-icon ⧖
          h4 Merkle Trees
          p Compact transaction proofs using hierarchical hash integrity.
        .theory-tool-card
          .theory-tool-icon ⛏
          h4 Proof of Work
          p Make history expensive to rewrite via computational asymmetry.

    //- ── Section 2: Hash Properties ─────────────────────────────────────────
    .theory-section
      h2.theory-section-title
        span.theory-section-number 2
        | Hash Functions: The Foundation
      p
        | Bitcoin uses <strong>double SHA-256</strong>:
        | <code>H(x) = SHA256(SHA256(x))</code>, producing a 256-bit (64 hex character) output.
        | This is applied to block headers, transaction identifiers, and Merkle trees.
      .theory-props-grid
        .theory-prop
          .theory-prop-label P1. Deterministic
          .theory-prop-desc Same input → always same hash. Every node on the network can independently verify results.
        .theory-prop
          .theory-prop-label P2. Avalanche Effect
          .theory-prop-desc One bit change → completely different hash. Small modifications cannot be hidden.
        .theory-prop
          .theory-prop-label P3. Preimage Resistance
          .theory-prop-desc Given h, infeasible to find m with H(m) = h. Hashes cannot be reversed.
        .theory-prop
          .theory-prop-label P4. Collision Resistance
          .theory-prop-desc Infeasible to find m ≠ m′ with H(m) = H(m′). Two different blocks cannot share a hash.
      .theory-avalanche
        h4 Avalanche Effect — Try it yourself on the Hash page:
        table.theory-table
          thead
            tr
              th Input
              th SHA-256 output (first 32 characters)
          tbody
            tr
              td
                code "Satoshi"
              td
                code.hash-value 54e3a30cb1b2698da3ed6e66ba...
            tr
              td
                code "satoshi"
              td
                code.hash-value 5f70bf18a086007016e948b04a...
        p.theory-note
          em One letter differs (S → s) — the outputs are completely unrelated.

    //- ── Section 3: Block Structure ─────────────────────────────────────────
    .theory-section
      h2.theory-section-title
        span.theory-section-number 3
        | Block Structure
      p
        | A Bitcoin block has two parts: a fixed-size <strong>header</strong> (80 bytes)
        | and a variable <strong>body</strong> of transactions (up to 1 MB).
      .theory-block-diagram
        .theory-block-part.theory-part-header
          .theory-block-part-label BLOCK HEADER — 80 bytes (this is what gets hashed)
          .theory-field-row
            .theory-field.field-version
              .theory-field-name Version
              .theory-field-size 4 bytes
            .theory-field-annotation Block format version number
          .theory-field-row
            .theory-field.field-prev
              .theory-field-name Previous Block Hash
              .theory-field-size 32 bytes
            .theory-field-annotation.annotation-key
              span.annotation-arrow →
              | This is what <strong>chains</strong> the blocks together
          .theory-field-row
            .theory-field.field-merkle
              .theory-field-name Merkle Root
              .theory-field-size 32 bytes
            .theory-field-annotation.annotation-merkle
              span.annotation-arrow →
              | Fingerprint of <strong>all transactions</strong> in this block
          .theory-field-row
            .theory-field.field-time
              .theory-field-name Timestamp
              .theory-field-size 4 bytes
            .theory-field-annotation Unix time when miner started working on this block
          .theory-field-row
            .theory-field.field-bits
              .theory-field-name Bits (difficulty target)
              .theory-field-size 4 bytes
            .theory-field-annotation Compact encoding of the current mining difficulty
          .theory-field-row
            .theory-field.field-nonce
              .theory-field-name Nonce
              .theory-field-size 4 bytes
            .theory-field-annotation.annotation-mine
              span.annotation-arrow →
              | <strong>Miners vary this</strong> until H(header) &lt; target
        .theory-block-part.theory-part-body
          .theory-block-part-label BLOCK BODY — variable (up to 1 MB)
          .theory-field-row
            .theory-field.field-txs
              .theory-field-name Coinbase transaction + tx₁, tx₂, … txₙ
              .theory-field-size ≤ 1 MB
            .theory-field-annotation The actual financial transactions recorded

      .theory-callout.callout-info
        strong Why only the header is hashed?
        br
        | The 80-byte header is hashed twice per mining attempt.
        | If the full block (up to 1 MB) were hashed, mining would be ~12,500× slower.
        | The <strong>Merkle Root</strong> in the header already commits to all transactions —
        | changing any transaction changes the Merkle Root, which changes the header hash.

      //- Field-by-field guide
      h3.theory-subsection-title Field-by-Field Explanation
      .theory-field-guide
        .theory-field-entry
          .theory-field-entry-name.bg-version Version
          .theory-field-entry-body
            p A 4-byte integer indicating which set of Bitcoin protocol rules to apply. Block version 1 (2009), version 2 (BIP34, 2012), version 3 (BIP66, 2015), etc.
        .theory-field-entry
          .theory-field-entry-name.bg-prev Previous Block Hash
          .theory-field-entry-body
            p The SHA256d hash of the <em>previous block's header</em>. This is the link that creates the chain. The genesis block (block #0) uses a previous hash of all zeros.
            .theory-mini-formula
              | H(header<sub>n-1</sub>) → stored as prev_hash in block n
        .theory-field-entry
          .theory-field-entry-name.bg-merkle Merkle Root
          .theory-field-entry-body
            p A single 32-byte hash that represents <em>all</em> transactions in the block. It is computed bottom-up from a binary tree of transaction hashes (see Section 5). Changing even one transaction changes this root — and therefore the entire block header hash.
        .theory-field-entry
          .theory-field-entry-name.bg-time Timestamp
          .theory-field-entry-body
            p Unix time (seconds since 1 Jan 1970) when the miner began hashing this block. Used to adjust mining difficulty every 2,016 blocks (~2 weeks) to target one block per 10 minutes.
        .theory-field-entry
          .theory-field-entry-name.bg-bits Bits / Difficulty Target
          .theory-field-entry-body
            p A compact 4-byte representation of the 256-bit target T. A valid block must satisfy H(header) &lt; T. A smaller T means harder mining (more leading zeros required).
            .theory-mini-formula
              | Current Bitcoin: ~70 leading zero bits required ≈ 5×10²⁰ hashes per valid block
        .theory-field-entry
          .theory-field-entry-name.bg-nonce Nonce
          .theory-field-entry-body
            p A 4-byte number (0 to 4,294,967,295) that miners increment trying to find a valid hash. This is the only field miners change freely. If all ~4 billion nonces fail, miners also vary the timestamp or extra-nonce in the coinbase transaction.

    //- ── Section 4: Chain Linking ────────────────────────────────────────────
    .theory-section
      h2.theory-section-title
        span.theory-section-number 4
        | Linking Blocks: The Chain
      p
        | Each block header contains the hash of the <strong>previous block's header</strong>.
        | This creates an unbreakable chain: you cannot modify a past block without
        | invalidating every block that follows.

      .theory-chain-visual
        .theory-chain-block
          .theory-chain-block-title Block 0 — Genesis
          .theory-chain-block-field.field-prev-display
            span.field-label prev:
            span.field-val.hash-zero 0000…0000
          .theory-chain-block-field
            span.field-label data:
            span.field-val tx₁
          .theory-chain-block-field
            span.field-label nonce:
            span.field-val n₀
          .theory-chain-block-hash
            span.field-label hash:
            span.field-val.hash-value H₀
        .theory-chain-arrow
          .arrow-line
          .arrow-label H₀ links →
        .theory-chain-block
          .theory-chain-block-title Block 1
          .theory-chain-block-field.field-prev-display
            span.field-label prev:
            span.field-val.hash-link H₀
          .theory-chain-block-field
            span.field-label data:
            span.field-val tx₂
          .theory-chain-block-field
            span.field-label nonce:
            span.field-val n₁
          .theory-chain-block-hash
            span.field-label hash:
            span.field-val.hash-value H₁
        .theory-chain-arrow
          .arrow-line
          .arrow-label H₁ links →
        .theory-chain-block
          .theory-chain-block-title Block 2
          .theory-chain-block-field.field-prev-display
            span.field-label prev:
            span.field-val.hash-link H₁
          .theory-chain-block-field
            span.field-label data:
            span.field-val tx₃
          .theory-chain-block-field
            span.field-label nonce:
            span.field-val n₂
          .theory-chain-block-hash
            span.field-label hash:
            span.field-val.hash-value H₂

      h3.theory-subsection-title Toy Numerical Example
      p
        | Using a simplified hash <code>h(x) = x mod 100</code>
        | for hand calculations (not cryptographic — for illustration only):
      table.theory-table
        thead
          tr
            th Block
            th prev
            th data
            th hash
            th Computation
        tbody
          tr
            td 0
            td 00
            td 10
            td
              strong 10
            td h(00 + 10) = h(10) = 10
          tr
            td 1
            td 10
            td 20
            td
              strong 30
            td h(10 + 20) = h(30) = 30
          tr
            td 2
            td 30
            td 50
            td
              strong 80
            td h(30 + 50) = h(80) = 80

      h3.theory-subsection-title Tamper Evidence
      .theory-tamper-demo
        .tamper-col
          .tamper-header.tamper-original Original Chain
          .tamper-block
            | Block 0: data=10, H₀ = 10
          .tamper-arrow ↓
          .tamper-block
            | Block 1: prev=10, data=20, H₁ = 30
          .tamper-arrow ↓
          .tamper-block
            | Block 2: prev=30, data=50, H₂ = 80
        .tamper-col
          .tamper-header.tamper-attack Attacker changes Block 1 data: 20 → 21
          .tamper-block
            | Block 0: unchanged, H₀ = 10
          .tamper-arrow ↓
          .tamper-block.tamper-broken
            | Block 1: prev=10, data=<strong>21</strong>, H₁ = <strong>31</strong> ≠ 30
          .tamper-arrow ↓
          .tamper-block.tamper-broken
            | Block 2: expects prev=30, but sees 31 → <strong>INVALID</strong>
      .theory-callout.callout-warning
        strong Why the attacker cannot fix this silently:
        | &nbsp;To fix Block 2, the attacker must recompute its hash — and then also redo its
        | <strong>Proof of Work</strong> (Section 6), which takes the entire network's computing
        | power about 10 minutes per block. With thousands of blocks in the chain,
        | this is computationally infeasible.

    //- ── Section 5: Merkle Trees ─────────────────────────────────────────────
    .theory-section
      h2.theory-section-title
        span.theory-section-number 5
        | Merkle Trees: Efficient Verification
      p
        | A block may contain thousands of transactions. The
        | <strong>Merkle tree</strong> (Merkle, 1987) solves verification efficiently
        | with a hierarchical hash structure.
      .theory-merkle-visual
        .merkle-level.merkle-root-level
          .merkle-node.merkle-root
            .merkle-node-label Root
            .merkle-node-val H(H₁₂ ∥ H₃₄)
        .merkle-level
          .merkle-node.merkle-inner
            .merkle-node-label H₁₂
            .merkle-node-val H(h₁ ∥ h₂)
          .merkle-connector
          .merkle-node.merkle-inner
            .merkle-node-label H₃₄
            .merkle-node-val H(h₃ ∥ h₄)
        .merkle-level
          .merkle-node.merkle-leaf.proof-node
            .merkle-node-label h₁
            .merkle-node-val H(tx₁)
          .merkle-node.merkle-leaf.proof-highlight
            .merkle-node-label h₂
            .merkle-node-val H(tx₂)
          .merkle-node.merkle-leaf.proof-node
            .merkle-node-label h₃
            .merkle-node-val H(tx₃)
          .merkle-node.merkle-leaf
            .merkle-node-label h₄
            .merkle-node-val H(tx₄)
        .merkle-level
          .merkle-node.merkle-tx.proof-node
            | tx₁
          .merkle-node.merkle-tx.proof-tx
            | tx₂ ← verify this
          .merkle-node.merkle-tx.proof-node
            | tx₃
          .merkle-node.merkle-tx
            | tx₄
      .theory-callout.callout-info
        strong Merkle Proof for tx₂:
        | &nbsp;To prove tx₂ is in the block, you only need h₁ and H₃₄ —
        | just 2 hashes instead of all 4 transactions.
        | For a block with 1,000,000 transactions, you need only log₂(10⁶) ≈ 20 hashes (640 bytes)
        | instead of transmitting the entire 1 MB block.

    //- ── Section 6: Proof of Work ────────────────────────────────────────────
    .theory-section
      h2.theory-section-title
        span.theory-section-number 6
        | Proof of Work: Mining
      p
        | Mining is the process of finding a <strong>nonce</strong> such that the block
        | header hash is below the target T (i.e., starts with enough leading zeros):
      .theory-formula-box
        | Find nonce such that:&nbsp;&nbsp;
        strong SHA256(SHA256(header ∥ nonce)) &lt; T
      .theory-mining-steps
        .mining-step
          .mining-step-num 1
          .mining-step-text Assemble the block header with current transactions and timestamp.
        .mining-step
          .mining-step-num 2
          .mining-step-text Set nonce = 0. Compute H = SHA256d(header).
        .mining-step
          .mining-step-num 3
          .mining-step-text Check: does H start with the required number of leading zeros?
        .mining-step.mining-step-branch
          .mining-step-yes
            strong YES →
            | Broadcast the block. Collect the block reward.
          .mining-step-no
            strong NO →
            | Increment nonce by 1. Return to step 2.
      .theory-mining-numbers
        h4 Real Bitcoin Numbers
        table.theory-table
          thead
            tr
              th Parameter
              th Value
          tbody
            tr
              td Target block time
              td 10 minutes
            tr
              td Difficulty adjustment
              td Every 2,016 blocks (~2 weeks)
            tr
              td Leading zeros currently required
              td ~70 bits
            tr
              td Average hashes per valid block
              td ~5 × 10²⁰
            tr
              td Global network hash rate (2024)
              td ~5 × 10²⁰ hashes/second

    //- ── Section 7: Security ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
    .theory-section
      h2.theory-section-title
        span.theory-section-number 7
        | Security: The 51% Attack
      p
        | To rewrite history (e.g. reverse a payment), an attacker must build an
        | <strong>alternative chain</strong> longer than the honest chain.
        | This requires controlling more than 50% of the total network hash rate.
      table.theory-table
        thead
          tr
            th Confirmations
            th Attacker hash rate
            th Probability of success
        tbody
          tr
            td 1
            td 10%
            td ~20%
          tr
            td 3
            td 10%
            td ~0.1%
          tr
            td 6
            td 10%
            td ~0.0001%
          tr
            td 6
            td 30%
            td ~0.17%
      .theory-callout.callout-warning
        strong The Bitcoin standard is 6 confirmations (~60 minutes).
        | &nbsp;This reduces attack success probability to negligible levels even against well-resourced adversaries.

    //- ── Section 8: Key Takeaways ────────────────────────────────────────────
    .theory-section
      h2.theory-section-title
        span.theory-section-number 8
        | Key Takeaways
      .theory-takeaways
        .theory-takeaway
          .takeaway-num 1
          .takeaway-text
            | The <strong>80-byte header</strong> is the cryptographic core of a block.
            | It commits to the entire block through the Merkle Root.
        .theory-takeaway
          .takeaway-num 2
          .takeaway-text
            | The <strong>Previous Hash</strong> field is the link that creates the chain.
            | You cannot silently modify a past block.
        .theory-takeaway
          .takeaway-num 3
          .takeaway-text
            | <strong>Proof of Work</strong> makes rewriting history computationally expensive —
            | the attacker must redo all the work done by the honest network since the target block.
        .theory-takeaway
          .takeaway-num 4
          .takeaway-text
            | <strong>Merkle trees</strong> allow lightweight nodes (phones, wallets) to verify
            | individual transactions without downloading the full blockchain.
        .theory-takeaway
          .takeaway-num 5
          .takeaway-text
            | <strong>Hash functions</strong> tie everything together: one-way, deterministic,
            | and with the avalanche effect that makes every field in the header matter.

